Even when I went into other stores as a former size 24, when I couldn't fit their clothing, but could buy accessories, they again, treated me with the dignity and respect that anyone, regardless of size deserves.

There's plenty of retailers such as GAP, H&M and Laura, to name a few, where their associates gladly treat me like a human being and help me find clothing in my size without being rude or condescending.
After this mortifying experience at the store, I would rather go naked than buy an article of clothing from any of your locations... but wait, I won't have to.
If she would have asked what size I was looking for, and then offered selections on the rack that fit my size, that would have been wholly acceptable.
This associate needs to learn how to offer assistance to customers in a way that isn't prejudiced. It's rude of her to automatically presume to know someone's size.

I've previously been a size 24 and I know from the experiences of being obese and now being at a more normal size, what fits my body. I also know when someone is being rude and judgemental based on my experience as a former plus size woman.
For reference, in standard women's sizing, I fit anywhere between a 12 to 16 (large to extra large) depending upon the fabric and fit of the clothing.

Your associate was adamant that I only look at items on this one rack. I finally, due to my discomfort and now feeling shamed for even setting foot in the store, told her I was looking for gift ideas for my mom, and then quickly left the store after that.

What I am upset about is that less than a minute after my response, your associate decided to covertly body shame me by pointing me to a rack that had exclusively extra large and bigger on it; with an assumption that I am larger than I actually am.

My response was that I was just browsing, because I really was browsing the different styles of clothing on the racks. I'm perfectly fine with your associate offering help right away. As a retail employee myself, I'm thrilled when people greet me when I enter a store.
